%N A396273 Decimal expansion of the probability that if three dice are piled up at random on a horizontal plane the pile will not fall down.
%C A396273 The problem is two-dimensional. Three identical squares are placed in a plane with positions and orientations that are independently and uniformly selected at random. Given that the second square overlaps the first and the third square overlaps the second, this constant is the probability that the center of mass of the second and third squares falls within the area of the first square.
%H A396273 Benjamin F. Finkel, <a href="https://www.jstor.org/stable/2968643">Biography: E. B. Seitz</a>, The American Mathematical Monthly, Vol. 1, No. 1 (1894), pp. 3-6. See p. 5.
%H A396273 Benjamin F. Finkel, <a href="https://www.jstor.org/stable/3028458">A History of American Mathematical Journals</a>, National Mathematics Magazine, Vol. 16, No. 6 (1942), pp. 284-289. See p. 286.
%H A396273 Artemas Martin, <a href="https://archive.org/details/mathematicalque18unkngoog/page/n189/mode/1up">Problem 3202</a>, in: W. J. C. Miller (ed.), Mathematical Questions and Solutions, Vol. 50,  F. Hodgson, London, 1889, p. 190.
%H A396273 Enoch Beery Seitz, <a href="https://babel.hathitrust.org/cgi/pt?id=mdp.39015040382486&amp;seq=169">Solution of the "Three-Dice" Problem</a>, The Mathematical Visitor, Vol. 1, No. 5 (1880), p. 157.
%F A396273 Equals (Pi/(Pi+4)^2) * (Pi/4 + 1/96 - sqrt(2)/12 + log(sqrt(2)-1)/12).
%e A396273 0.0372363798163572124026938819120854296544114623719828...
